        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>local SEO heatmap</strong> is a color-coded visual representation of how a business ranks at multiple geographic coordinate points within its service area. Green indicates Local Pack positions 1-3, yellow shows positions 4-7, and red reveals positions 8 and below. It converts geo grid rank tracking data into a geographic map that immediately shows where local visibility is strong and where it drops off.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Grid radius</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-15 miles typical</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Green zone</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Positions 1-3</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Standard rank tracking tells you where you rank. A local SEO heatmap tells you where you rank depending on where the searcher is standing. For a business with a physical location or defined service area, that distinction matters — your position in the Local Pack changes with every mile.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a local SEO heatmap?</h2>
        <p>A local SEO heatmap is generated by a geo grid rank tracking tool. The tool selects a keyword, places the business at the center of a geographic grid, and simulates Google searches from dozens of coordinate points spread across the grid — typically spaced 1-3 miles apart. At each coordinate, it records what position the business holds in the Local Pack for that keyword. The result is a heat-map overlay on a geographic map showing the full ranking landscape across the service area.</p>

        <p>The color coding follows a standard convention:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Green (positions 1-3):</strong> Prime Local Pack placement. The business appears in the 3-box for searchers in this zone.</li>
          <li><strong>Yellow (positions 4-7):</strong> Below the fold. The business appears if the searcher expands "more results" or scrolls the map.</li>
          <li><strong>Red (positions 8+):</strong> Invisible for practical purposes. Few users scroll past position 7 in local results.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why location changes your local rank</div>
          <p>Google's local algorithm weighs proximity heavily. A business that ranks 1st for a searcher standing across the street may rank 8th for someone 5 miles away — even if nothing else about the query or the business has changed. Heatmaps make this proximity decay visible and measurable.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local SEO heatmaps matter for your strategy</h2>
        <p>Standard rank trackers report a single position number. That number is meaningless for local businesses because it doesn't specify where the search was performed. A heatmap solves this by showing the full geographic picture:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Identify true competitive gaps.</strong> Red zones near your business location signal a problem — likely citation gaps, category mismatches, or review deficits that a stronger competitor doesn't have.</li>
          <li><strong>Target content geographically.</strong> Red zones 3-5 miles out that you should own can be addressed with neighborhood-specific landing pages, hyperlocal content, and local link building targeted to those areas.</li>
          <li><strong>Demonstrate ROI to clients.</strong> Before/after heatmaps are the clearest visual proof of local SEO progress. A law firm that expanded its green zone from a 2-mile to a 6-mile radius has a compelling before/after story that a rank position number alone can't tell.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive mapping.</strong> Running heatmaps on your top 2-3 competitors reveals where they are dominant and where gaps exist. Neutral territories with no strong incumbent are the highest-ROI areas to target first.</li>
          <li><strong>Service area decision-making.</strong> If you are considering expanding to a new neighborhood or city, running a heatmap shows how far your current GBP authority reaches before decay sets in.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How local SEO heatmaps are generated</h2>
        <p>The generation process runs in four steps:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keyword selection:</strong> Choose a keyword representing a core service (e.g., "emergency plumber," "family dentist," "personal injury attorney"). Run separate heatmaps for each major service keyword — rankings vary significantly by keyword even for the same business.</li>
          <li><strong>Grid configuration:</strong> Set the center point (your business location) and grid radius (typically 3-15 miles depending on service area size). Tighter grids reveal hyperlocal nuance; wider grids show service area reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Automated scanning:</strong> The tool queries Google from each grid coordinate, recording the Local Pack position for the chosen keyword. A 9x9 grid generates 81 data points; a 13x13 grid generates 169. Most tools complete scans within minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>Map overlay generation:</strong> Results are color-coded and overlaid on a geographic map. You see at a glance which neighborhoods you dominate and which you're invisible in.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="url-flow">
