        <h2 id="examples">Real local SEO heatmap examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Personal injury law firm — before/after optimization</h3>
        <p>A personal injury firm's initial heatmap showed green concentrated within a 2-mile radius of their downtown office, with red covering everything beyond. After 6 months of work — citation cleanup, 22 new Google reviews, 4 neighborhood-specific landing pages, and weekly GBP posts — the follow-up heatmap showed green extending to a 6-mile radius. The visual before/after made the ROI case instantly to the firm's managing partner, who had been sceptical about local SEO investment.</p>

        <h3>2. Dental practice — competitive mapping</h3>
        <p>A dental practice generated comparative heatmaps for themselves and three nearby competitors using the keyword "family dentist [city]." The analysis revealed one competitor dominated the northern neighborhoods while the practice held strong in the south. The eastern half of the service area showed weak rankings from all four businesses — no clear incumbent. The practice shifted content production and local link outreach toward the east, and within 4 months captured strong local pack positions in that previously neutral territory.</p>

        <h3>3. Multi-location cleaning company — budget allocation</h3>
        <p>A residential cleaning service launched in three cities simultaneously with equal marketing budgets. After 60 days, heatmaps for each city revealed drastically different green zone coverage — one city showed broad coverage, two showed narrow green near the business center. The company reallocated budget from the underperforming cities toward the one showing organic strength, and within 30 days the strong city was generating 3x the leads of the others combined.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local SEO heatmap vs. standard rank tracking</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a heatmap when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need geographic visibility — not just a number</li>
              <li>You serve a defined service area with multiple neighborhoods</li>
              <li>You want to identify which zones need content or link targeting</li>
              <li>You need to report local SEO progress to a client visually</li>
              <li>You're running a competitive gap analysis</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use standard rank tracking when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need organic (non-Local Pack) rank monitoring</li>
              <li>You're tracking national keywords without geographic variation</li>
              <li>Budget is limited — standard tracking is cheaper per keyword</li>
              <li>You're monitoring historical trends across many keywords</li>
              <li>Local Pack is not your primary traffic source</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for local SEO heatmap analysis</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Run heatmaps per service keyword, not just brand name.</strong> Your rankings for "emergency plumber" and "water heater installation" often look completely different — the heatmap is only useful if it shows the keyword you want to rank for.</li>
          <li><strong>Establish a monthly baseline before making changes.</strong> Run a heatmap on day 1 of any local SEO campaign. Without a before snapshot, you can't quantify the after improvement.</li>
          <li><strong>Map competitors, not just yourself.</strong> A heatmap showing your competitor's green coverage reveals exactly which neighborhoods to target for maximum competitive impact.</li>
          <li><strong>Create neighborhood content for red zones inside your service area.</strong> Red zones within 3 miles of your business that should logically be covered are the highest-priority content gap — a dedicated neighborhood page often moves those zones from red to yellow within 60 days.</li>
          <li><strong>Pair heatmap data with citation and review audits.</strong> Red zones near the business center that persist after months of work usually indicate a citation inconsistency or review volume gap relative to whoever is holding that position. Fix the underlying signal, not just the content.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — over-scanning</div>
          <p>Running daily heatmap scans is wasteful. Local Pack rankings are relatively stable — day-to-day changes are minor and usually noise, not signal. Monthly scans show meaningful movement. Over-scanning burns through tool credits and produces data you can't act on fast enough to matter.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local SEO heatmap mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Scanning only for your brand name</strong> — Your brand always ranks well near your location. Scan for the commercial keywords customers actually use.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring competitor heatmaps</strong> — Your own heatmap shows where you are weak. Competitor heatmaps show why — and where to attack.</li>
          <li><strong>No before/after baseline</strong> — Without a pre-campaign scan, you cannot measure what your optimization efforts actually moved.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating all red zones equally</strong> — Red zones adjacent to your business need different fixes than red zones 10 miles away. Near-business red is a signal problem; distant red is a coverage problem.</li>
          <li><strong>Scanning too infrequently</strong> — Monthly is the minimum. Quarterly scans miss the early signs of competitor gains or algorithm shifts that erode your coverage.</li>
        </ul>

